# TypeScript

## Strict Typing

- All code must be strictly typed
- NEVER use `any` — use `unknown` if the type is unknown
- Avoid `@ts-ignore` and `@ts-expect-error` — fix the problem instead of suppressing it
- Always specify return type for public functions

## Types vs Interfaces

- Use `type` for union types, mapped types, utility types
- Use `interface` for objects that can be extended
- Be consistent within a module

## Type Imports

- Use `import type` for importing only types — this improves tree-shaking

## Generics

- Use descriptive names for generics: `TUser`, `TResponse`, `TInput`
- Or standard names: `T`, `K`, `V` for simple cases

## Validation Schemas

The project uses TypeBox and Zod for validation. Extract types from schemas using `Static` (TypeBox) or `z.infer` (Zod).

## Nullable Types

- Use `null` for explicit "absence of value"
- Use `undefined` for "not set" or optional fields

## Utility Types

Use built-in TypeScript utility types: `Partial`, `Pick`, `Omit`, `Required`, etc.
